        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-11-20T19:50:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-11-20T19:50:00-05:00" n="366"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d366">
                <head>366. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in the United Arab Republic</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d366fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, POL 27 US-<gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss>. Secret. Drafted by
                            <persName corresp="#p_JGLJ1">Jones</persName> on November 19; cleared by
                            <persName corresp="#p_BWB1">Buffum</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_STW1">Seelye</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_KAI1"
                            >Killgore</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_DRP1">Davies</persName>, and
                            <persName corresp="#p_JJD2">Jernegan</persName>; and approved by
                            <persName corresp="#p_TPH2">Talbot</persName>. Repeated to Jidda,
                        London, Taiz, Amman, and <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1963-11-20T19:50:00-05:00">November 20, 1963, 7:50 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2227. Department trusts <gloss target="#t_UARG1">UARG</gloss> sufficiently
                    reassured by President’s statement on US aid (<gloss target="#t_Depcirtel1"
                        >Depcirtel</gloss> 900)<note n="1" xml:id="d366fn1">Dated November 14.
                        (Ibid., <gloss target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss> (US)) Reference is to remarks
                        made by President <persName corresp="#p_KJF2">Kennedy</persName> at his
                        press conference on November 14. Speaking in response to a question, the
                        President said that he did not think that the requirement of the <persName
                            corresp="#p_GE4">Gruening</persName> Amendment strengthened the U.S.
                        hand or flexibility in dealing with the <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss>,
                        but rather had the opposite effect. (<hi rend="italic">Public Papers of the
                            Presidents of the United States: <persName corresp="#p_KJF2">John F.
                                Kennedy</persName>, 1963</hi>, p. 850)</note> to be amenable to US
                    counsels to expedite Yemen disengagement. Immediate action is essential.</p>
                <p>This connection, USG notes: 1) evidence <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss>
                    forces Yemen remain at 30,000 level—contrary <persName corresp="#p_NGA1"
                        >Nasser</persName>’s assurances they would be reduced to 26,000 by November
                    1; 2) continued bombing royalist bases; 3) resumption <pb facs="0862" n="796"
                        xml:id="pg_796"/> bombing Saudi territory (Jidda’s 528).<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d366fn2">Dated November 19. (Department of State, Central Files, POL
                        32–1 SAUD-<gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss>)</note> If Embassy has not yet
                    transmitted Talbot’s six recommendations (<gloss target="#t_Deptel1"
                        >Deptel</gloss> 1937 to <gloss target="#t_UARG1">UARG</gloss>),<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d366fn3">Telegram 1937 to Cairo, November 6, contained a summary of
                        a conversation between <persName corresp="#p_TPH2">Talbot</persName> and
                        Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_KM2">Kamel</persName>, during which the two
                        discussed how to break the deadlock in Yemen. <persName corresp="#p_TPH2"
                            >Talbot</persName> urged that the United Arab Republic moderate
                        propaganda, broaden the government in Yemen, expand cooperation with <gloss
                            target="#t_UNYOM1">UNYOM</gloss>, stop rotating <gloss target="#t_UAR1"
                            >UAR</gloss> units into Yemen, evacuate the demilitarized zone, and stop
                        the bombings. (Ibid., POL 27 YEMEN)</note> suggest this action should be
                    taken now. We leave to your discretion means of transmittal—whether by letter
                    from Ambassador to Nasser, conversation between Embassy officer and Presidency
                    official, or otherwise.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss>: If <gloss target="#t_UARG1">UARG</gloss>
                    genuinely seeks detente with Amman and Riyadh, repatriation of defected aircraft
                    might be effective gesture. Embassy may wish consider utility allusion to this
                    possibility on appropriate occasion.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_JJE1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Johnson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
